In TypeScript, you can use the type assertion operator "as" to explicitly tell the type system that a value has a specific type in practice, but not necessarily in theory. For example:
```ts
let a: string = 'foo';
let b: number = 42;

type X = string | number;

let x: X = a as X;
let y: X = b as X;
```
The above code will assign "foo" to the variable "x", and will assign "42" to the variable "y", because the type assertion operator says that although in theory "a" may have any type, in practice it will only have the type string. The type assertion operator allows you to tell the type system that in practice, a value may have multiple types, but that it will always have a specific type.

This is a simple example of how to count the occurrences of a specific word in a text file using C++.

Here is the code:
```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    ifstream file("input.txt");
    string line;
    int count = 0;

    while (getline(file, line))
    {
        if (line.find("word") != string::npos)
        {
            count++;
        }
    }

    cout << count << endl;

    return 0;
}```

